## What is "almost"?

Now, to the second part.

Let's try and be scholars about this "almost" thing. Say you have %%foo%% and you have %%foo_{almost}%% which is defined as "almost foo". Then there must be a small-ish difference between %%foo%% and %%foo_{almost}%%. Mathematicians love to use an uppercase Greek letter "delta" to indicate differences, so we'll do the same:

$$
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta_{foo} & = & foo - foo_{almost} \\
foo_{almost} & = & foo - \Delta_{foo} \\
\end{eqnarray}
$$

Obviously.

It is also implied (much rather from the dictionaries than from any kind of math definitions) that the magnitude of "almost foo" is comparable to %%foo%% itself. This makes our %%\Delta_{foo}%% insignificant enough, which means it's smaller than both %%foo%% and %%foo_{almost}%%.

{.sidenote}
Note how I chose to avoid tossing absolute values in the picture when discussing magnitudes. It doesn't make that much difference for the argument, but can become increasingly annoying when juggling equation terms.

$$
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta_{foo} & < & foo              \\
\Delta_{foo} & < & foo_{almost}     \\
\end{eqnarray}
$$

## What is "almost infinity"?

Now to find %%\infty_{almost}%%. Let's substitute our %%foo%% with %%\infty%%:

$$
\begin{eqnarray}
\infty_{almost} & = & \infty - \Delta_\infty \\
\Delta_\infty & < & \infty \\
\Delta_\infty & < & \infty_{almost} \\
\end{eqnarray}
$$

So we need to find such %%\Delta_\infty%% and %%\infty_{almost}%% which satisfies all the of the above equations.

1. Let's first assume %%\Delta_\infty \in \Bbb R%%, which means it's a real number, say a gazillion (a real gazillion).
    Let's call it %%r%% now, for simplicity.

    - It [definitely](#inf-1) satisfies the %%\Delta_\infty < \infty%% part...

    - ...but it [also](#inf-2) means that:

        $$\infty_{almost} = \infty - \Delta_\infty = \infty - r = \infty$$

    - ...which leads us to suggest that:

        $$\Delta_\infty = \infty - \infty_{almost} = \infty - \infty$$

    - ...which we [know](#inf-5) to be %%undefined%%...

    - ...which is a contradiction to our original assumption.

    Math guys hate contradictions, so it's an end of story. %%\Delta_\infty%% is not a real number.

2. What else can %%\Delta_\infty%% be to satisfy our equations?

    - It can be something smaller than %%\infty%%, but not a real number.

    - %%\sqrt{\infty}%%, perhaps? Yup, why not, it still [satisfies](#inf-6) the %%\Delta_\infty < \infty%% equation.

    - Since I don't trust myself with calculating %%\infty - \sqrt{\infty}%%, I had to [ask for help](https://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=infinity+-+sqrt%28infinity%29):

        {.centered.shadow}
        ![](/img/misc/infinity minus sqrt infinity.png)

    - Ah, our good friend %%undefined%%, good to see you again.

    This assumption does not hold true, because %%\sqrt{\infty} \neq undefined%% (because, well, square root of infinity is sort of defined, in mathematical terms at least).

3. Feels like we're running out of assumptions on %%\Delta_\infty%%: we've tried arbitrary real numbers, we've tried powers of infinities. Seems like everything we try results in us converging on %%\Delta_\infty%% being %%undefined%% in the end. Which ruins our assumptions.

    Unless we assume that %%\Delta_\infty%% *is* %%undefined%%.

    Then our %%\infty_{almost} = \infty - undefined = ...%%

    🥁🥁🥁

    Of course, it's %%undefined%%.

    🎉🎉🎉

    But wait. We said it has to satisfy all three equations. Does %%\Delta_\infty = undefined%% satisfy %%\Delta_\infty < \infty%% and %%\Delta_\infty < \infty_{almost}%%?

    $$
    \begin{eqnarray}
    undefined & < & \infty \\
    undefined & < & undefined \\
    \end{eqnarray}
    $$

    The answer to both is %%undefined%%.

Which, incidentally, is the answer to our original dilemma. %%\blacksquare%%

